Great Western Champagne.
America's oldest continuous champagne winery. Named as
the "Great" champagne of the "Western world. Founded
1860 - U.S. Bonded Winery #1.
Frankfurters.
Reputedly came from Frankfurt, Germany and introduced to
this country in the 1880's by a Bavarian gentleman who sold
them together with a pair of cotton gloves to prevent his cus-
tomers from burning their fingers.
Poached Fillets of Sole Diamond Jim.
Diamond Jim started out as the son of a poor saloon keeper
and rose to be a wealthy man as a pioneer of the railroad era.
A man who showed his wealth through wearing ornate dia-
mond jewelry and gifting his friends and associates with the
same. A man whose girth was matched only by his incredible
appetite for gourmet foods.
Sourdough Rolls.
Possibly the oldest of bread recipes dating as far back as 4000
B.C. It is made with a sourdough "starter," a self perpetuat-
ing yeast mixture made with a combination of flour, sugar
and water. It became identified in America through its use by
the Alaskan sourdoughs, prospectors who carried "starters"
strapped to their packs so that they could make bread any-
time without having to walk to the nearest town.
Waldorf Salad.
The original recipe was created by one of the most famous
of Maitres d'Hôtel, Oscar of the Waldorf.
Salt Water Taffy.
This candy, almost a tradition is sold along the boardwalk
at Atlantic City. Rumor has it that it is made with sea water.
Cover.
One of a series of photographs depicting Early 19th Century
cooking utensils from New England, in wood, tin, ceramic,
cast and handwrought iron.
